article.description: Tony Parker had 27 points and nine assists, and the Spurs increased their lead in the Western Conference to one game by beating the SuperSonics 104-95.
article.headline: Spurs beat Sonics, take one-game lead in West
article.linkText: Spurs beat Sonics, take one-game lead in West
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Tony Parker caught Tim Duncan's flu-like symptoms. He avoided the shooting woes. Parker had 27 points and nine assists, and the San Antonio Spurs increased their lead in the Western Conference to one game by beating the Seattle SuperSonics 104-95 Tuesday night. Duncan, who was 3-of-12 from the floor entering the fourth quarter, complained of aches and a fever last week. Now Parker has the bug. "This morning I woke up with a headache and a sore throat," Parker said. "It was kind of tough. I didn't know if I could play. But Will [Sevening, the Spurs trainer] said to try, so I did." Parker shot 13-of-19. He was 7-of-8 from the field in the second quarter to help San Antonio build a seven-point lead at halftime. The Spurs outscored Seattle 23-9 through the first 9:43 of the second half to take a 21-point lead. The Spurs led by 19 with 3:46 to go when they pulled their starters. Duncan finished with 18 points and 14 rebounds, but he shot 6-of-18 and was 6-for-12 from the free throw line. San Antonio (60-18) recorded a 60-win season for the third time in franchise history, the last coming when the Spurs won the NBA title in the 2002-03 season. San Antonio coach Gregg Popovich wasn't excited to hit 60 wins. "That's not the goal," he said. "The goal is to get better every day going into the playoffs." The Spurs lead Dallas by a game for the best record and the top seed in the West. Both teams have four regular-season games remaining -- with all the Spurs' games against teams with losing records. Seattle (33-44) had won a season-best four straight games and six of the past eight. Ray Allen averaged 31 points and shot 55.4 percent during the winning streak, but was limited to 14 points and shot 5-of-13 from the floor. The Spurs outshot Seattle 50 percent to 38 percent. San Antonio had a season-best 13 blocks. "This game was about our complete lack of execution on offense," said Allen, who had 10 points on 3-of-9 shooting heading into the fourth quarter. "We just couldn't put the ball in the basket." Luke Ridnour and Rashard Lewis each scored 15. Brent Barry, inserted into the starting lineup in place of injured Manu Ginobili, scored 16 points. He shot 6-of-12, including 4-for-8 from 3-point territory. Ginobili missed his second straight game because of left calf and shin bruises. The Spurs won both games with Ginobili out of the lineup. Michael Finley came off the Spurs' bench to score 17 points. He hit 3-of-4 3-pointers. The Sonics led by six points 9:36 into the game. But the Spurs went on a 13-0 run during the next 4:02 to take a 31-22 lead on Parker's layup. San Antonio took its largest lead of the half when Parker scored on a fast-break layup to make it 47-37 with 4 minutes left. Parker had five assists in the first quarter, including two in the final 2:11 when Rasho Nesterovic hit three straight shots for the Spurs. Nesterovic made his first five shots to open the game.

Game notes
The Spurs have won 60 games two other times in team history, including a franchise-best 62 in 1994-95. ... Besides Ginobili's absence, Spurs forward Robert Horry missed the game when he attended to family business after the death of his father-in-law. ... Spurs reserve point guard Beno Udrih played for the first time since a sprained left ankle forced him to miss the past six games. ... SuperSonics forward Chris Wilcox entered the game with four consecutive double-doubles, but he scored eight points and had six rebounds against the Spurs.
